vectorData.altText: 6. The _______________ nerve is associated with cutaneous sensation over the posterior aspect of the arm and lateral hand, as indicated by the letter A.
That's right!  The radial nerve is responsible for cutaneous sensation over the posterior aspect of the arm, forearm and lateral hand.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Recall that the radial nerve with its companion, the deep brachial artery, crosses the posterior aspect of the humerus in the spiral (radial) groove. The radial nerve innervates the triceps, and the skin overlying the posterior aspect of the arm.
The muscular branches of the radial nerve to the three heads of the triceps arise in the proximal arm. Therefore, for a lesion of the radial nerve to affect elbow extension, it must occur proximal to these branches.
The radial nerve continues into the posterior compartment of the forearm to innervate all of its contained muscles.
